\par\pard\plain \li950\fi-475\sl360\slmult1\qj\ltrch\loch \ls1\ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs24\b0\i0	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs24\b0\i0 Edit the Title Page document to ensure it contains the correct information.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs24\b0\i0	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs24\b0\i0 Create a new text document for each scene inside the \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93Act\u8221\'94 folder. You can choose Project > New From Template > New Scene (also available from the binder\u8217\'92s Ctrl-click contextual menu) or click the drop-down arrow beside the green \u8220\'93Add\u8221\'94 button in the toolbar to access the document types. Choosing \u8220\'93New Scene\u8221\'94 will create a scene that already has the scene heading entered for you (note that the \u8220\'93<$N>\u8221\'94 in the scene headings will be changed to sequential numbers upon compile, but if you prefer you can delete them and write the numbers manually). The template for the \u8220\'93New Scene\u8221\'94 document is contained in the \u8220\'93Templates\u8221\'94 folder (documents in that folder can be used as the basis for new documents and appear in the New From Template menu).}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs24\b0\i0	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs24\b0\i0 You can create more \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93Act\u8221\'94 folders if you wish, although this is not necessary.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs24\b0\i0	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs24\b0\i0 Ensure you are in script mode (Format > Scriptwriting > Script Mode) when typing your scenes (when in script mode, the footer bar will show the script elements instead of the word and character count, and the document icon in the binder will be yellowish).}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs24\b0\i0	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs24\b0\i0 When typing dialogue, do not enter the colon after the character name. Instead, just hit the tab key\hich\f2 \emdash \loch\f2 the colon will be inserted for you. You can add names to the character element\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8217\'92s auto-complete list so that you don\u8217\'92t have to keep typing them out. To do this, open Format > Scriptwriting > Script Settings\u8230\'85 and select the Character & Dialogue element from the list on the left, then click the Auto-Complete tab and use the \u8220\'93+\u8221\'94 button to add new words.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs24\b0\i0	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs24\b0\i0 Characters, Settings and Notes folders have been set up for you, which you can use however you wish\hich\f2 \emdash \loch\f2 or you can delete them and create different folders to organise your project. (These are just regular folders that have had custom icons assigned to them using the Documents > Change Icon feature.)}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs24\b0\i0	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs24\b0\i0 Compile your manuscript for printing by selecting File > Compile.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f2\fs24\b0\i0	\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f2\fs24\b0\i0 BBC Radio format expects \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93page turns\u8221\'94 at the end of pages where dialogue is split and spills over to the next page\hich\f2 \emdash \loch\f2 for instance, \u8220\'93(CHARA #1/CONT\u8217\'92D OVER)\u8221\'94. Although a \u8220\'93Page Turns\u8221\'94 element is provided, it is usually awkward to add page turns during the drafting stage, so it is recommended that you instead add the page turns in a word processor after compiling your script, before you submit it. To do so, change the \u8220\'93Compile For\u8221\'94 setting of the Compile sheet to \u8220\'93Rich Text (.rtf)\u8221\'94, export your script, and open the generated RTF file in a word processor such as Microsoft Word, then go through the pages and add page turns wherever dialogue is broken across pages.}
